		<item>
		<title>Ambush Marketing: What It Is &#038; Why It Works</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/04/04/ambush-marketing</link>
					<comments>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/04/04/ambush-marketing#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dan Shewan]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 04 Apr 2018 05:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Marketing Ideas]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/04/04/ambush-marketing/</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>You've probably seen ambush marketing in action - but what is it, and why do so many brands risk getting into trouble by doing it? Let's explore the wild world of ambush marketing, with examples and tips for making it work.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/04/04/ambush-marketing">Ambush Marketing: What It Is &amp; Why It Works</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Ever found yourself telling someone about some good news you got, only for the other person to completely ignore what you said and start talking about themselves?</p>
<p>That‚Äôs a little what ambush marketing is like.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-sign-joc.gif" alt="Ambush marketing" width="640" height="552" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Image via <a href="https://www.joc.or.jp/english/aboutjoc/marketing.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Japanese Olympic Committee</a></em></p>
<p>Today we‚Äôll be taking a look at ambush marketing ‚Äì specifically, what it is, what it looks like, and why brands spend countless millions of dollars on glorified pissing contests.</p>
<p>We‚Äôll be examining the advantages and disadvantages of ambush marketing, including some real-world examples of how ambush marketing has been utilized to great effect by some of the world‚Äôs best-known brands.</p>
<p>First up, a primer on the basics.</p>
<h2>What Is Ambush Marketing?</h2>
<p>Ambush marketing ‚Äì also known as coat-tail marketing or predatory ambushing ‚Äì is the practice of hijacking or coopting another advertiser‚Äôs campaign to raise awareness of another company or brand, often in the context of event sponsorships.</p>
<p>One of the earliest known examples of ambush marketing is <a href="https://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/02/07/VISA-American-Express-battle-with-Olympic-ads/8877697438800/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the bitter feud that erupted between MasterCard and Visa</a> during the 1992 Winter Olympics, which was held in the town of Albertville in southeastern France.</p>
<p>Having paid $20 million (approximately $35.5 million in 2018 dollars) for the privilege, Visa was the official credit card sponsor of the ‚Äô92 Winter Games. For months prior to games, Visa ran TV commercials advising American Express cardholders to leave their AmEx at home as ‚Äúthe Olympics don‚Äôt take American Express.‚Äù</p>
<div>
<div class="video-embed-field-provider-youtube video-embed-field-responsive-video"><iframe width="854" height="480" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Pdn6WdnjXjA?autoplay=0&amp;start=0&amp;rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div>
</div>
<p>Technically, this was true ‚Äì tickets to the games could only be purchased with Visa credit cards. However, Visa‚Äôs aggressive ad campaign soon raised the ire of American Express, which claimed Visa‚Äôs ads were purposefully misleading by suggesting that American Express cards were not accepted <em>anywhere</em> at the ‚Äô92 Winter Games.</p>
<p>AmEx soon launched its own series of TV spots, which featured the slogan, ‚ÄúWhen you go to Spain, you‚Äôll need a passport ‚Äì but you don‚Äôt need a Visa,‚Äù a sly reference to the forthcoming Summer Games in Barcelona and <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/ambush-at-barcelona-rivals-are-piggybacking-official-sponsors-of-the-olympic-games-write-nick-1534185.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a subtle dig at the company‚Äôs rival</a>. American Express was accused by Visa of engaging in ‚Äúparasite marketing,‚Äù which later gave rise to the slightly more palatable name of ambush marketing.</p>
<h2>4 Real-World Ambush Marketing Examples</h2>
<p>Now that we‚Äôve looked at what ambush marketing is, it‚Äôs time to see some examples of this technique in action, from the inspired to the irreverent.</p>
<h3>#1: BMW vs. Audi</h3>
<p>Santa Monica, California, may be famous for its lengthy pier and near-perfect weather, but this affluent coastal city was also the battlefield upon which two of the world‚Äôs largest car manufacturers waged a war for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/02/26/out-of-home-advertising">billboard</a> dominance.</p>
<p>The spat began soon after BMW hosted a rally in Wisconsin, an event that was publicized through an accompanying campaign. The slogan of the campaign was ‚ÄúA BMW rally with two nearby service centers. What‚Äôs next, paramedics at a chess tournament?‚Äù</p>
<p>Crappy, nonsensical slogans aside, Audi saw an opportunity to capitalize upon BMW‚Äôs campaign. In response to BMW‚Äôs ads, Audi purchased a billboard in Santa Monica advertising its new A4 sedan and mocking BMW‚Äôs slogan:</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-audi-chess-billboard.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Audi vs. BMW billboard war Santa Monica" width="800" height="489" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Image via </em><a href="https://jalopnik.com/5213704/bmw-vs-audi-jalopnik-readers-turn-billboard-cold-war-hot" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Jalopnik</em></a></p>
<p>Not long after the billboard above appeared in Santa Monica, Audi doubled down and erected another giant roadside provocation to BMW, while cleverly sticking to BMW‚Äôs regrettable chess theme:</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-audi-your-move-billboard.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Audi vs. BMW billboard Your Move, BMW" width="529" height="323" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Image via </em><a href="http://www.thebrandingjournal.com/2015/01/benefit-billboard-brand-rivalry/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Branding Journal</em></a></p>
<p>BMW didn‚Äôt take this attack lying down. In response, BMW purchased an enormous billboard across the street from Audi‚Äôs billboard:</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-bmw-checkmate-billboard.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Audi vs. BMW billboard war Checkmate " width="800" height="475" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Image via Jalopnik</em></p>
<p>By now, you‚Äôd think that two of the world‚Äôs largest vehicle manufacturers would have tired of their childish tit-for-tat.</p>
<p>They hadn‚Äôt.</p>
<p>After BMW erected its ‚ÄúCheckmate‚Äù billboard response, Audi upped its game again by launching yet another billboard ad with yet another witty chess-related quip. Ultimately, BMW won the day with its final, withering response:</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-bmw-game-over-zeppelin.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Audi vs. BMW billboard war blimp game over" width="1280" height="720" /></div>
<p>Oh, and to really twist the knife, BMW actually tethered the blimp to Audi‚Äôs R8 billboard.</p>
<p><em>Savage</em>.</p>
<h3>#2: Paddy Power</h3>
<p>Unlike our friends in the States, many of whom seem to have an irrational, almost phobic aversion to a friendly wager, my countrymen in Britain love a good bet. Walk down any high street in the U.K. and you‚Äôll most likely see at least one or two bookmakers, among the best-known of which is Irish gambling chain Paddy Power.</p>
<p>Like so many of the most notorious ambush marketing campaigns, Paddy Power‚Äôs first foray into the exciting world of predatory ambushing took place during the Olympic Games ‚Äì the London 2012 Games, to be precise.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-paddy-power-london-2012-billboard.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Paddy Power London 2012 billboard campaign" width="642" height="507" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Image via </em><a href="http://adage.com/article/creativity-news/paddy-power-resists-olympic-ambush-ads-u-k/236305/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>AdAge</em></a></p>
<p>As the British capital geared up for the Games, Paddy Power launched a wide-scale billboard campaign across the city, claiming it was the ‚ÄúOfficial sponsor of the largest athletics event in London this year.‚Äù Below the bookmaker‚Äôs bold claim was a disclaimer that revealed Paddy Power was referring to the town of London, France ‚Äìthe event the ad referred to was not the Olympic Games, but rather a traditional egg-and-spoon race that Paddy Power really did sponsor.</p>
<p>The IOC took a predictably dim view of Paddy Power‚Äôs tongue-in-cheek campaign, and demanded the Irish bookie take down the ads immediately. Paddy Power challenged the IOC‚Äôs order in court, and <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/25/london-2012-paddy-power" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ultimately won its fight against the IOC</a> in a landmark ruling.</p>
<h3>#3: Samsung vs. Apple</h3>
<p>In October of 2011, Apple was preparing to launch the then-latest iteration of its flagship mobile device, the iPhone 4S.</p>
<p>The device launch was expected to be one of the most hotly anticipated tech events of the year ‚Äì so Samsung decided to crash Apple‚Äôs party by erecting a pop-up store just a few feet away from Apple‚Äôs prestigious storefront in Sydney, Australia.</p>
<p>While eager Apple acolytes (<em>Appolytes?</em>) waited patiently to get their hands on the new iPhone, Samsung proceeded to sell its Galaxy SII device for just $2 AUS ‚Äì mere pocket change compared to Apple‚Äôs $850 iPhone.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-samsung-vs-apple.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Samsung vs. Apple Sydney pop-up store iPhone 4S launch" width="779" height="439" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>LOL. Image via </em><a href="https://www.smh.com.au/technology/samsung-ambushes-apples-iphone-4s-launch-in-sydney-20111012-1lk0d.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Sydney Morning Herald</em></a><em>.</em></p>
<p>Plenty of people managed to resist Samsung‚Äôs tempting offer, but many more still chose to walk away with a brand-new Samsung device rather than wait in line for the iPhone 4S.</p>
<p>Although Samsung took an enormous financial hit with its iPhone launch event stunt (which we‚Äôll break down shortly), the incident proved just how easy it can be to ride the coat-tails of one of the world‚Äôs biggest brands.</p>
<p>You can find more great Apple marketing campaigns in our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/04/06/how-to-market-a-product">epic product marketing examples post</a>.</p>
<h3>#4: Rona and the iPods</h3>
<p>When you‚Äôre one of the wealthiest companies in the history of mankind, you can‚Äôt help but attract attention. Case in point, another classic ambush marketing example of a company leveraging Apple‚Äôs advertising to its own ends.</p>
<p>Back in 2010, Apple‚Äôs colorful iPod Nano was among the most popular MP3 players on the market (just typing this makes me feel ancient). To advertise its iPod Nano line, Apple erected a billboard ad next to the Jacques Cartier Bridge in Montreal displaying the vividly colorful MP3 players in a satisfying rainbow-ribbon arrangement.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-rona-paint-apple-ipod.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Rona paint Apple iPod billboard" width="800" height="439" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Image via </em><a href="https://www.coloribus.com/adsarchive/ambient/leftover-paint-collection-program-rona-chromatic-13277405/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Coloribus</em></a></p>
<p>Sensing an opportunity, Canadian paint and hardware firm Rona seized its chance. Rona soon erected its own billboard ad directly beneath Apple‚Äôs iPod ad to advertise the company‚Äôs new paint recycling program. The ad, which bore the slogan ‚ÄúNous r√©cup√©rons les restes de peinture,‚Äù or ‚ÄúWe collect leftover paint,‚Äù was brilliantly simple, and the ad remains one of the best and most creative examples of ambush marketing in recent memory.</p>
<h2>Why Use Ambush Marketing?</h2>
<p>Now that we know what ambush marketing is, let‚Äôs take a look at some of the advantages of this type of advertising campaign.</p>
<h3>Ambush Marketing Campaigns Can Be Very Clever</h3>
<p>Something I personally love about ambush marketing campaigns is how cheeky they can be and the <a href="/blog/ws/2016/06/06/local-marketing-ideas">creative flexibility</a> these campaigns offer.</p>
<p>Since most ambush marketing campaigns directly respond to or otherwise leverage an existing campaign by a close competitor, ambush campaigns can ‚Äì and often, have to ‚Äì be extremely creative. This includes everything from visual trickery to witty wordplay. As a result, ambush marketing campaigns are often a lot more memorable than a typical ad precisely because they‚Äôre unusually entertaining or clever.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-newcastle-brown-ale-vs-stella-artois.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Newcastle Brown Ale chalice campaign" width="320" height="480" /></div>
<p>Subtle references and sly jokes are often integral to the success of ambush marketing campaigns. As we saw in the Audi vs. BMW example above, ambush campaigns often respond directly to one another, which can turn visual humor into a vital competitive edge.</p>
<p>Even if one ad is ‚Äúbetter‚Äù than another, the funnier or cleverer ad <a href="/blog/ws/2013/10/08/funny-ads">will often be much more memorable</a>, as Newcastle Brown Ale proved in the example ambush campaign above.</p>
<h3>Ambush Marketing Campaigns Can Go Off-Script</h3>
<p>When it comes to display advertising ‚Äì online or IRL ‚Äì cohesion is crucial. From enormous, towering billboards in Times Square to a mobile sidebar ad, brands have to ensure that their campaigns <a href="/blog/ws/2013/10/15/multi-channel-marketing">look, feel, and sound the same across all platforms</a>.</p>
<p>Ambush campaigns, however, can get a little more creative.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-fiat-volkswagen-google-maps.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Fiat photobombs Volkswagen Swedish headquarters Google Maps" width="603" height="398" /></div>
<p>One of the key advantages of ambush marketing is that it allows brands to go off-script from their regular advertising campaigns, whether in <a href="/blog/ws/2014/07/31/brand-voice">style, tone, or content</a>. Brands can and frequently do employ techniques that may be beyond the scope of a company‚Äôs established brand or advertising guidelines, affording the ambusher a great deal more creative freedom and flexibility.</p>
<p>Italian car manufacturer Fiat leveraged this principle to great effect in an impromptu ambush campaign back in 2013 when Fiat somehow managed to park a red Fiat 500 hatchback car on the front steps of Volkswagen‚Äôs Swedish headquarters ‚Äì just in time for a Google Maps car to pass, which preserved Fiat‚Äôs little stunt for years in Google Maps results. (The offending little red Fiat is no longer immortalized in Maps results, as Google refreshed the old image with a newer image that was taken in June of 2017).</p>
<h3>Ambush Marketing Can Change Consumer Perceptions</h3>
<p>Another benefit of ambush marketing is that, done well, it can actually help brands cultivate and exhibit new <a href="/blog/ws/2017/11/15/website-copy">brand attributes and values</a> that consumers may not necessarily already associate with that advertiser.</p>
<p>Take South African airline Kulula, for example. To coincide with the 2010 World Cup, Kulula launched an ad campaign branding itself as the ‚ÄúUnofficial National Carrier of the You-Know-What,‚Äù a not-so-subtle reference to the forthcoming soccer tournament. The World Cup‚Äôs governing body, FIFA, demanded that Kulula cease the campaign immediately, claiming that the airline sought ‚Äúto gain a promotional benefit for the Kulula brand by creating an unauthorized association with the 2010 FIFA World Cup.‚Äù</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-sepp-blatter-boston-terrier.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Sepp Blatter Boston Terrier" width="575" height="384" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Sepp Blatter, the real MVP</em></p>
<p>Though unhappy with FIFA‚Äôs decision, Kulula reluctantly complied with FIFA‚Äôs order. However, the airline wasn‚Äôt done quite yet. Shortly after the ads were pulled, Kulula said it would fly anyone named Sepp Blatter ‚Äì the name of FIFA‚Äôs then-president ‚Äì for free. Eventually, the airline located <a href="https://twitter.com/seppthedog">a Boston Terrier</a> that shared a name with FIFA‚Äôs former president, and made the improbably named pup an unofficial mascot.</p>
<p>This campaign serves as a great example of how ambush marketing can help brands cultivate new brand values. Air travel is an insanely competitive industry, but Kulula‚Äôs ambush campaign not only gained the airline some invaluable publicity, but also advanced the idea that Kulula isn‚Äôt just another dry, boring airline.</p>
<h2>What Are the Disadvantages of Ambush Marketing?</h2>
<p>So, we‚Äôve looked at how and when ambush marketing can work well, but this approach is not without its downsides.</p>
<h3>Ambush Marketing Can Be Very Expensive</h3>
<p>The main drawback of ambush marketing is that it has the potential to be very expensive.</p>
<p>Take the very public spat between Audi and BWM in Santa Monica above, for example. For the sake of argument, let‚Äôs assume that <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/08/business/the-media-business-rarefied-billboard-air-of-the-sunset-strip.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a billboard in Santa Monica costs $10,000 per month</a> (not including actual design or printing costs). The fight between Audi and BMW lasted for several months and resulted in four separate billboard ads running simultaneously in the same geographic location, which almost definitely drove costs up even further. Then BMW went and put a zeppelin above all four billboards, which can cost anywhere between $500,000 and $5 million. So far, we‚Äôre talking almost $100,000 on the billboards alone, plus the cost of BMW‚Äôs blimp, plus all design and production costs.</p>
<p>Not exactly small change.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-hindenburg-disaster.jpg" alt="Ambush marketing Hindenburg disaster" width="657" height="524" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>The Hindenburg, also known as ‚Äúyour advertising budget‚Äù</em></p>
<p>Ambush marketing might seem like a great way to piggy-back on another brand‚Äôs efforts ‚Äì and it can be ‚Äì but it also demands a certain level of spend that puts this approach beyond the reach of smaller companies or newer, less established brands. That‚Äôs why ambush campaigns tend to be launched by well-funded brands at major international events like the Olympics or the Super Bowl ‚Äì it‚Äôs so expensive, the return has to be worthwhile.</p>
<h3>Calculating the ROI of Ambush Marketing Is Very Difficult</h3>
<p>Another problem with ambush marketing campaigns is that <a href="/blog/ws/2016/10/21/calculate-roi-offline-transactions">calculating the ROI</a> of such a campaign can be very difficult, if not actually impossible.</p>
<p>Take our Samsung hijacking example from earlier. In terms of the upfront overhead costs, Samsung‚Äôs little stunt in Sydney wasn‚Äôt that expensive. There was the cost of refurbishing the pop-up store itself and the wages of the Samsung employees who manned the store during the event.</p>
<p>The <em>real</em> cost of this ambush marketing campaign was the massive hit that Samsung took on each individual Galaxy SII device sold during the event.</p>
<p>Time for some napkin math!</p>
<p>First, we need to establish the base cost of a Galaxy SII device. For the sake of example, let‚Äôs say that a Samsung Galaxy SII cost $499, which is what the device retailed for at launch in many regions.</p>
<p>Next, we need to determine how many Galaxy SII devices Samsung sold during its ambush marketing event. For our purposes, we‚Äôll say that the Samsung pop-up store sold 750 Galaxy SII devices that day.</p>
<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/ambush-marketing-samsung-pop-up-store-sydney.jpeg" alt="Ambush marketing Samsung vs. Apple Sydney pop-up store iPhone 4S launch" width="420" height="280" /></div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Fans wait outside Samsung‚Äôs pop-up store in Sydney in 2011. Image via</em><br />
<a href="https://thenextweb.com/apple/2011/10/12/samsung-plays-dirty-ambushes-apples-iphone-4s-launch-in-sydney/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Next Web</em></a><em>.</em></p>
<p>Finally, we need to figure out how much it cost Samsung to put on its event in Sydney. Let‚Äôs say Samsung hired two people to staff the pop-up store, paid each of them $15 per hour (ha!), and asked them to work for eight hours each. This means our staffing costs would be $240. Now let‚Äôs say that it cost Samsung $10,000 to actually refurbish the store. Using these figures, we can say that Samsung‚Äôs ambush marketing event cost $10,240.</p>
<p>If this were a typical ad campaign, we might use the following formula to come up with some numbers:</p>
<p><strong>Value of a Galaxy SII</strong> <em>multiplied by</em> <strong>Number of devices sold</strong> <em>minus</em> <strong>Event overhead costs</strong></p>
<p>Since we know that a Galaxy SII costs $499, that Samsung sold 750 devices during the event, and spent $10,240 to actually put on the event itself, the formula above would look like this:</p>
<p>499 x 750 ‚Äì 10,240 = 364,010</p>
<p>So, using the monkey math above, we could say that Samsung‚Äôs ambush marketing campaign generated $364,010 in revenue ‚Äì not bad for a pop-up store!</p>
<p>But wait a minute ‚Äì wasn‚Äôt Samsung was selling its Galaxy SII devices for just $2? Now our math looks a lot less attractive:</p>
<p>2 x 750 ‚Äì 10,240 = -8,740</p>
<p>Going by the actual numbers, <strong>Samsung actually lost almost $9,000 in revenue</strong> because it was selling its Galaxy SII devices for just two bucks..</p>
<p><em>This</em> is how much it really cost Samsung to put on its event in Sydney.</p>
<p>For our purposes, we‚Äôre not actually interested in that figure. For a global brand like Samsung, $364,000 is couch change. What we want to know is whether the ambush marketing campaign was worth $364,000 ‚Äì and this is where it gets complicated.</p>
<p>You can‚Äôt assign numerical values to intangible factors such as <a href="/blog/ws/2017/03/06/brand-advertising-for-conversions">brand awareness</a> or positive consumer sentiment, which makes it very difficult to effectively gauge the ROI of an ambush marketing campaign. It‚Äôs easier to gauge the overall reception of an ambush campaign by monitoring mainstream and social media for <a href="/blog/ws/2013/04/25/social-media-roi">mentions, links, and other engagement metrics</a>, but when you get down to brass tacks, proving the financial ROI of an ambush marketing campaign can be <em>very</em> difficult.</p>
<h3>Time and Space Are Factors in Ambush Marketing</h3>
<p>Another problem with ambush marketing campaigns is that in addition to the potential costs involved, these campaigns often require a relatively quick response or coordinated planning (or both) if they‚Äôre to work effectively or successfully leverage the target campaign to achieve its goal. To complicate matters further, the availability and price of advertising inventory can make or break an ambush marketing campaign before it even gets off the ground.</p>
<p>Take Newcastle Brown Ale‚Äôs ‚Äúchalice‚Äù campaign above, for example. Although these ads were quite memorable, their effectiveness relied solely upon the neighboring Stella Artois ads they mocked; by themselves, Newcastle Brown Ale‚Äôs ads would only be memorable because they wouldn‚Äôt make any sense (and for potentially confusing American passersby with their use of the word ‚Äúbollocks‚Äù).</p>
<p>This means that time and space are crucial factors in many ambush marketing campaigns. Unless you can be sure that the target of your ambush campaign will be there for a while ‚Äì such as a sports stadium with a corporate sponsor or something similarly semi-permanent ‚Äì you need to move quickly.</p>
<h2>It‚Äôs a Trap!</h2>
<p>Ambush marketing isn‚Äôt a viable marketing strategy for most businesses. The costs involved can be prohibitively expensive to all but the wealthiest of brands, but the underlying strategies beneath ambush marketing as a concept can be easily applied to your campaigns, from PPC campaigns on the search network to primarily visual campaigns on Facebook.</p>
<p>Hopefully, this post has given you some creative inspiration for new approaches you can take to your existing ads. Next time you sit down to write or optimize your next campaign, consider what you could learn from the examples above. You might not get to rub a competitor‚Äôs face in it with a gigantic billboard in Times Square, but you <em>might</em> be able to poke a sly dig at your competitors in your next Facebook campaign.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/04/04/ambush-marketing">Ambush Marketing: What It Is &amp; Why It Works</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
